g src=http://server3002.freeyellow.com/oggs/Bldshrdhead.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Yeah, multiple reasons.</span><hr size=1> 1) Lawsuits &amp; liability. <br>
Someone performs a deal on an on-line auction site. Deal goes bad. Person decides to sue everyone involved. If EQ backed on line auctions then they could be found at partial fault.<br>
<br>
2) No $$ to be made. <br>
As was stated above. No money to be made for Sony. I make a character, get it to 60th. I sell my character for $300. I made $300. Sony made $0. They are a business after all.<br>
<br>
3) Wasting customer service man hours.<br>
Additional waste of customer service resources on something beyond Sony's control, such as scams involved with on-line auctions. Bobby spends $100 for a level 60 warrior. That warrior only comes with half the gear that was listed. Person selling warrior insists it had it all &amp; states Bobby should get EQ customer service involved. Additional resources are wasted on tracking this all down.<br>
<br>
Also, all kinds of additional customer service manpower wasted (financially at least) on things like name changes, account billing info changes &amp; such.<br>
<br>
4) It's a game to be played not won.<br>
Plus the pure aspect of EQ is made to be a game played, not a game won. Verant likes to support the idea that hopefully you'll have as much fun playing a level 1 player as a level 60 &amp; tries to build around that.<br>
 <p><b>
Bloodshard Ogg</b>
