The only one I'm not sure about is #2. It seems if there were no aftermarket for accounts, a lot of people leaving the game would simply cancel their account. With selling them they continue the subscription. To me it seems more likely that a person who plays casually and has a level 30 character would be more likely to cancel their subscription than someone who has a level 60 character with mostly nodrop gear. It seems that a lot of the accounts get bought up by people who have multiple accounts already, and are willing to spend $50/mo and upwards maintaining all of them, rather than people who are just getting into the game and buy an account in lieu of starting their own subscription and starting from level 1. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uaraxasxev.showPublicProfile?language=EN>araxas xev</A> at: 1/30/02 5:04:25 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uaanadien.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aanadien</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Safehouse Supporter</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/30/02 6:14:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22025.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.vanessarussell.com/Phank/jumppavitarsmall.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The reason is to protect themselves from liability</span><hr size=1> The reason Verant officially frowns upon the trade in gear and accounts for real-world dollars while making only token efforts to actually fight the trade is, I think, obvious:<br>
<br>
In case some twit ever gets it into his head to sue Verant for damages relating to the loss of his toon or some gear due to some alleged negligence on the part of Verant or their employees, Verant doesn't want to be caught on the record recognizing the real-world monetary value of game objects.<br>
